  <span id="freeText12910156406570339757" style="display:none">I was in between books and found this under my bed. I think that when I asked for some book donations from parents for my class library four or five years ago and this one was in the mix I didn't think it was appropriate to keep at school. How it ended up under my bed I don't know. Broken was a pretty powerful personal account of William Cope Moyers, who is the son of LBJs press secretary (among his many other credentials), and his personal story was pretty powerful. The message that addiction is a disease that doesn't just go away like a cold was strong and profound. It's easy to forget the disease part of drug and alcohol addiction and also sad that the stigmas attached to addiction are still so negative and dismissive. Moyers's story, including the lapses and relapses into addiction, were a pretty powerful reminder that in life taking it one day at a time and savoring what you have vs. what you think you need is really the only way to go. Having a brother that has struggled for most of his life with addiction made this book a little more personal for me. My hope for him and anyone else struggling with drug and alcohol addiction is that they gather the strength and courage to keep fighting and battling until they understand and own their disease, seek help, and stay healthy for the rest of their lives. </span>
