  <span id="freeText14012755529227369068" style="display:none">The author's story was somewhat compelling. However I was confused by some of the reasons for his resorting to crack and alcohol, why was it he needed to dull "pain", what was the pain? Just alluding to the father's success and how this in some way (?) negatively affected the author, that raesoning did not "wash" with me and so I was never really clear on WHY the author decided he NEEDED to be numbed to his apparently very happy life, successful career, and<br />wonderfully understanding family. The parents and grandparents (according to the author's own memories and testimony), were all extraordinarily loving, caring and supportive. The saved letters from the father were additional evidence of his deep love and pride in his son. The author did not suffer deprivation, hunger, physical abuse or any other kind of abuse. I was left completely baffled and not really very sympathetic I am afraid. Although one thing the author did say stuck with me, he realized he had always felt put-upon and needing pity, nothing was ever fair. Although he grew up in a Christian home, the realization of sin and pride and ego did not penetrate. Hopefully, from the epilogue, one can conclude there was a change for Christ that lasted.</span>
